  <article xml:id="samplewks" label="0000"><!-- Change label to a random string of numbers for each worksheet. The label shows up in the url of the website and keeps students from searching for other worksheets -->
    <title>MATH 142 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
      For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
      </p>
    </introduction>
  <!--START TYPING CONTENT FOR SESSION BELOW HERE-->
  <worksheet>
    <title> Session #1 (Sections 1.1-1.3)</title><!-- SECTION 1-->
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
      <!--'&' and '<' are exceptional characters and are instead authored as &amp; and &lt;. See 4.1.4.2-->
    </p>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>
    <exercise workspace="0.75in"><!-- #1 --><!-- controlling workspace length is the best way to force page breaks on a worksheet -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain the meaning of of <m>\D\lim_{x \to 3} f(x) = -2</m>. <!--see 4.9 in Guide for displaying mathematics-->
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="0.75in"><!-- #2 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
         If <m>\D\lim_{x \to 2} g(x) = 7</m>, then <m>\D\lim_{x \to 2^-} g(x)</m> <fillin/>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="0.75in"><!-- #3 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
        If <m>\D\lim_{x \to 8^-} h(x) = \frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>\D\lim_{x \to 8^+} h(x) = -\frac{4}{3}</m>, 
        then <m>\D\lim_{x \to 8} h(x)</m> <fillin/>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="0.75in"><!-- #4 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
         If <m>\D\lim_{x \to -6^-} p(x) = \sqrt{5}</m> and <m>\D\lim_{x \to -6^+} p(x) = \sqrt{5}</m>, then 
        <m>\D\lim_{x \to -6} p(x)</m> <fillin/>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="0.75in"><!-- #5 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
         If <m>\D\lim_{x \to 0^-} h(x) = e</m>, what do we know about <m>\D\lim_{x \to 0} h(x)</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    </paragraphs>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>
    <exercise number="1"><!-- #1 --><!-- must restart numbering manually for each section -->
      <statement>
        <p>Complete the graph below so <m>f(x)</m> has the domain <m>[-8,7]</m>, <m>\D\lim_{x \rightarrow -4} f(x)=-2</m>, 
          and <m>\D\lim_{x \rightarrow 5^-} f(x)=9</m>. 
        <image source="M142_HOGU_session1_fig1.png" width="70%"> <!--this is how you include an image. Upload image to the "assets" folder--><!--see 4.14 in Guide for more info-->
          <shortdescription>Graph of a piecewise-defined function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription><!--This is what a screenreader reads. Do not include math mode here.-->
          <description><!--this is not automatically read by a screenreader, but user can navigate there. Math mode is acceptable here and paragraph environment must be included-->
            <p>
             The graph of a piecewise-defined function <m>f(x)</m> plotted on coordinate axes.
             The function is a parabola with vertex at the point <m>(-6, 10)</m> and endpoints at <m>(-8,-2)</m> and <m>(-4,-2)</m> where
             <m>(-8, -2)</m> is a closed circle and <m>(-4,-2)</m> is an open circle. The point <m>(-4, 8)</m> is a closed circle. 
             The function is linear with open endpoint <m>(-2,2)</m> and closed endpoint <m>(3,12)</m>, and again linear
             with closed endpoints <m>(5,4)</m> and <m>(7,-4)</m>.
             No graph is given between <m>x=-4</m> and <m>x=-2</m>, and between <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=5</m>.
            </p>
          </description>
        </image>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise workspace="1in" number="2"><!-- #2 -->
      <statement>
        <p>Complete the tables below to estimate  <m>\D\lim_{t \rightarrow 0} \frac{|t-5|}{t}</m> numerically. 
          If the limit does not exist, state so and use limit notation to describe any infinite behavior. Round your answers to four decimal places (if necessary).
        <!--see chp 20 on Guide for how to create tables-->
          <p>
            Left-Hand Limit:
          </p>
          <tabular halign="center">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
              <cell>Variable <m>t</m></cell>
              <cell>Variable <m>f(t)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.1</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.01</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.001</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.0001</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          
          <p>
            Right-Hand Limit:
          </p>
          <tabular halign="center">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
              <cell>Variable <m>t</m></cell>
              <cell>Variable <m>f(t)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0.1</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0.01</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0.001</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0.0001</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  
  
    <exercise workspace="2in" number="3"><!-- #3 -->
      <statement>
        <p> Set up a table to estimate <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow -2} \frac{x^2-x-6}{(x+2)(x+7)}</m> numerically. 
          When creating your table, show at least three <m>x</m>-values approaching <m>-2</m> from each side and their corresponding function values in the table. 
          If the limit does not exist, state so and use limit notation to describe any infinite behavior. 
          Round your answers to four decimal places (if necessary).  
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise workspace="2in" number="4"><!-- #4 -->
      <statement>
        <p> Given the graph of <m>f(x)</m> below and <m>g(x)=\frac{10x-30}{x^2-x-6}</m>, 
          find <m>\D\lim_{x \rightarrow 3} \left( \frac{f(x)+5x}{2}+\sqrt{g(x)+14} \right)</m>. 
          <image source="M142_HOGU_session1_fig2.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription> The graph of a piecewise-defined function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
          <description>
            <p>
             The graph of a piecewise-defined function <m>f(x)</m> plotted on coordinate axes.
             The function is a parabola with vertex at the point <m>(-6, 10)</m> and endpoints at <m>(-8,-2)</m> and <m>(-4,-2)</m> where
             <m>(-8, -2)</m> is a closed circle and <m>(-4,-2)</m> is an open circle. 
             The function is linear with open endpoint <m>(-4,-2)</m> and closed endpoint <m>(-2,10)</m>. 
             The function is linear with open endpoints <m>(-2,2)</m> and <m>(3,12)</m>.
             The function is again linear with open endpoint <m>(3,12)</m> and closed endpoint <m>(5,12)</m>.
             The points <m>(-4, 8)</m> and <m>(3,4)</m> are closed circles. 
             There is no graph to the left of <m>x=-8</m> or to the right of <m>x=5</m>.
            </p>
          </description>
        </image>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  
  
    <exercise number="5"><!-- #5 -->
        <introduction><!-- instead of a statement, use an introduction followed by tasks when authoring multiple choice problems.-->
          <p>
            Given <m>\D f(x)= \begin{cases}5^{4x-3}&#x26;x \leq -5\\ \\  \D \frac{x^2-x}{x^2+2x}&#x26;x>-5 \\\end{cases}</m> find the following limits.
            If the limit does not exist, state so and use limit notation to describe any infinite behavior.
            Round your answers to four decimal places (if necessary).
          </p>
        </introduction>
          <!-- see 4.11 for making lists and different options for markers-->
            <task workspace="2in">
              <p>
                <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 0}f(x)</m>
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="2in">
              <p>
                <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow -2^+}f(x)</m>
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="2in">
              <p>
                <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow -5}f(x)</m>
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 
  
    <exercise number="6"><!-- #6 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> Find the following limits algebraically. If the limit does not exist, state so and use limit notation to describe any infinite behavior. 
          Round your answers to four decimal places (if necessary). 
        </p>
      </introduction>
            <task workspace="1.3in">
              <p>
                <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow e}\left( x^{3}+\ln(2x-e) \right)</m>
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="1.3in">
              <p>
                <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 9}\frac{\sqrt{x}-3}{x-9}</m>
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="1.3in">
              <p>
                <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 3}\frac{x^{2}+3x}{x^{2}+6x+9}</m>
              </p>
            </task>
            <task workspace="1.3in">
              <p>
                <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow -3}\frac{x^{2}+3x}{x^{2}+6x+9}</m>
              </p>
            </task>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="7"><!-- #7 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> For each graph below, find the indicated limit.</p>
      </introduction>
          <task>
            <sidebyside widths ="75% 25%" valign ="middle"><!-- see 4.24 for more on side-by-side -->
            <p>
            <image source="M142_HOGU_session1_fig3.png" width="70%">
              <shortdescription>Graph of a function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
              <description>
                <p>
                  Graph of a function <m>g(x)</m> plotted on coordinates axes. The graph decreases from the top left corner, dips below the <m>x</m>-axis and then 
                  increases until it encounters a vertical asymptote at <m>x=1</m>. To the right of <m>x=1</m>, the function increases until it leaves the coordinate axes
                  on the top right. 
                </p>
              </description>
            </image> 
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol marker="(i)">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow \infty}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow -\infty}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^+}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^-}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 1}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
      </task>
          <task>
            <sidebyside widths ="75% 25%" valign ="middle">
            <p>
              <image source="M142_HOGU_session1_fig4.png" width="70%">
              <shortdescription>Graph of a function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
              <description>
                <p>
                  Graph of a function <m>g(x)</m> plotted on coordinate axes. Starting on the left, the graph increases away from, but never touches, the horizontal asymptote
                  <m>y = -6</m>. The graph reaches a peak above the <m>x</m>-axis, and then decreases along, but never touching the vertical asymptote <m>x=3</m> until it leaves 
                  the coordinate axes. The graph then increases to the right of the vertical asymptote, approaching but not touching the horizontal asymptote <m>y = -6</m>
                  until it leaves the coordinate axes.
                </p>
              </description>
            </image> 
            </p>
            <p>
            <ol marker="(i)">
              <task>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow \infty}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </task>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow -\infty}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 3^+}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 3^-}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow 3}g(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
      </task>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="8"><!-- #8 -->
      <introduction>
        <p> Jenn is trying to find <m>\D\lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} f(x)</m> given  <m>f(x) = \frac{12+4x^7+x}{-19x^6+2x^2-5x^7}</m>. </p>
      </introduction>
          <task workspace="1.5in">
            <p>
              Jenn starts by evaluating the limit <m>x \to \infty</m> of the numerator and of the denominator separately,
              but gets the indeterminant form <m>\D\frac{\infty}{-\infty}</m> for the overall limit.
              She then remembers a technique from math class: <em>when evaluating limits at infinity, divide every term in
              the numerator and denominator by the term with the highest power in the denominator</em>.
              What should she divide each term by? What is the result after division?  
              <!--See 4.1 for acceptable markups in paragraphs. Note that there is (intentionally) no option to bold text.-->
            </p>
          </task>
          <task workspace="2in">
            <p>
              The next step is to take the limit <m>x \to \infty</m> of <em>each</em> term in <m>f(x)</m> as rewritten in part (a).
              For example, the term <m>\D\frac{12}{x^{7}}</m> goes to <m>0</m> as <m>x \to \infty</m>.
              We can indicate this by writing <m>\D\cancelto{{0}}{\frac{12}{x^{7}}}</m>.
            </p>
          </task>
          <task workspace="0.5in">
            <p>
              Use part (b) to find the exact value of <m>\D \lim_{x \rightarrow \infty}f(x)</m>.
            </p>
          </task>
    </exercise> 
  
  </paragraphs>
  
  <paragraphs>
    <title>Now Grades Go Up</title>  
    <exercise number="1"><!-- #1 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          The mathematical notation <m>\D\lim \limits_{x \rightarrow 5} f(x)</m> means <m>\underline{ \qquad\qquad}</m>
          <!-- see 4.11 for making lists and different options for markers-->
             <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p>we need to find the value of the function  at <m>x=5</m>.</p> </li>
                <li> <p> we need to investigate the <m>y</m>-values of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> gets very near <m>x=5</m> from both the left and right sides of <m>x=5</m>, 
                  but not necessarily at <m>x=5</m>.</p> </li>
                <li> <p>we need to find the horizontal asymptotes. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> we need to find the instantaneous rate of change.</p> </li>
                <li> <p> we need to investigate the <m>y</m>-values as we approach <m>x=5</m> only on the right side.</p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="2"><!-- #2 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
           Find <m>\D\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}</m>. If the limit does not exist, but has infinite behavior, use limit notation to 
                describe the infinite behavior of the function as <m>x \longrightarrow 2^-</m>.
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p> <m>\D {\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}=3</m></p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}=-\infty</m></p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}</m> DNE, 
                  but has infinite behavior that can be described as <m>\D{\lim_{x \rightarrow 2^-} f(x) \rightarrow -\infty}</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p><m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}</m> DNE, 
                  but has infinite behavior that can be described as <m>\D{\lim_{x \rightarrow 2^-} f(x) \rightarrow \infty}</m>. </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>\D {\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}=0</m> </p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="3"><!-- #3 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>\D\lim \limits_{x \rightarrow 7} \frac{x^2-8x+7}{x-7}</m>.
              <ol marker="(a)">
                <li> <p> <m>0</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> DNE </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>6</m>  </p> </li>
                <li> <p> <m>8</m> </p> </li>
                <li> <p> None of these. </p> </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </paragraphs>
</worksheet>

  </article>

